Praetor interrogat eum qui cedit an contra vindicet, 2 ξ 24; cf. 4 § 1.6. It was not necessary that the oross claime of the parties should be identical in character. On the one eide there might be a claim of status, on the other of property, one party vindicating as free the person whom another claimed as slave : or one party vindicating the frcedom of a person whom another, as transferes of patria potestas, claimed to be his bondeman (mancipium); or one party asserting the independence (sui juris) of a person whom another claimed as filius familias or as subject to patria potestas, cf. 1 ξ 134.

Similarly under the legis actio procedure Hereditatis petitio, 3 ξ 32, comm, would probably be in the form of judicium duplex3 for Hereditatis petitio is a species of Vindicatio.
